Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey intended to join the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of Bosporus, perhaps just 20 steps from the European border, there is one of the greatest relics of the failed imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neo-renaissance style.
At least that's what the guidebooks say.
The building embraces the end of the platforms, each with a tower on each front corner, and looks like a German rural town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building's going a little crazy.
However, looking at the interior of the vaulted ticket office, it is evident that this was the most western doorway of a large enterprise.
The station was opened by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation in August 1908.
Germany, the "late future" of conquests, sought to achieve its ambitions to occupy the Middle East by means of this railway from Damascus to Baghdad to today's Saudi Arabia.
German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence and his Arab partisans in Arabia.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The British colonial army left Egypt and forced the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
Hyderpasha Station didn't do any better.
In 1917 an ammo train exploded and destroyed the building's beautifully designed roof.
According to Turkish sources, there's been a sabotage operation.
Since then, it has slowly fallen apart, and history has gone far beyond it.
At the same time, today, as the gateway to the railway to Anatolia and the entire eastern region, it serves as, at least symbolically, an expanding diplomatic horizon for Turkey.
The Justice and Development Party on the Government - the AKP - has developed a whole new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The new policy is marked by commitment.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian groups of Hamas and Fatah, Iraq, Iran and, of course, the European Union and the United States.
I wanted to assess the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I took the night train to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, the Turkish Member of Parliament, Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, after about ten and a half hours of tumbling, which gave me the rhythm of the famous documentary "The Night Mail" about the old world, I arrived in the Turkish capital. The new city is intended to symbolize the new secular state, which turns its back on the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP with known Islamic roots represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This caused some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern, stone and steel, specifically designed for this purpose, which is located in a developing suburban district between half-finished shopping centers and cafés. In the latter, the mid-leaders in suits - both men and women - meet to make a deal early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu would have fit in with a right-to-middle politician in any other European country.
He was wearing a suit, a tie, and I'm sure he even had a Blackberry.
"The party's foreign policy goal is to help Turkey reintegrate into its immediate environment.
"The Cold War has upset order," he said.
Turkey is isolated from its hinterland.
He had to head east and west at the same time today.
He couldn't choose between the two.
He had to open both ways.
"But is it possible that sooner or later you will be forced to choose?" I asked.
"Turkey never wanted to go to a crossroads."
He then stressed what almost everyone I spoke to here was saying almost mechanically: Turkey's relations with not only the Middle East but also with the Caucasus and the countries around the Black Sea are of the same benefit to Europe and the United States as Turkey itself.
It is as if they are trying to convey the message that, metaphorically speaking, with Turkey, all of Europe can reach Asia and the Middle East on those east-bound railway lines.
When I was back at Hydarpasha Station, after another night spent most of the night awake, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conura, the two German gentlemen who watched this fancy structure recover 100 years ago.
How they would have been surprised to know that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East are now largely in Turkey's hands.
And as I waited for the ferry at the port to take me back through Bosporus, I remembered that Turkey was then called "the sick man of Europe."
At least at that time, there was no question which continent would claim this exciting country.
