The collision avoidance "bee car"
For the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired this time by nature, precisely from the world of bees, for its new invention.
The Japanese company designed a robot that imitates the flight of bees to avoid accidents.
Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C may be the first step in the development of collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Center built this little robot in Japan in cooperation with the Advanced Science and Technology Research Centre of the renowned Tokyo University.
Kazuhhiro Doi, Technological PR and Research Development Brand Director, defined BR23C as a further extension of the four-level safety shield of Nissan.
The robot enhances the impact avoidance capacity of the company's products.
During flight, each bee develops its oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
However, the role of the complex eye of the uterus is far more important than that, with which it can see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the complex eye, engineers designed a so-called laser telemeter (Laser Range Finder).
The apparatus identifies obstacles within a 180 degree field of vision before BR23C within a distance of up to 2 metres, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately transforms into an action to avoid collision.
"When an obstacle is detected, the small robot immediately changes direction by moving the wheels at a smaller or larger angle in order to avoid collision.
The main difference between the system and the instruments currently available is that in this case the bypass manoeuvre takes place entirely automatically.
If not, the robot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Andoh Toshiyuki, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
By way of derogation from bees, by-pass manoeuvres shall not be directed upward or downward, nor diagonally, shall they move only in two dimensions and only in the direction of wheel rotation, i.e. not in an infinite direction and way, as is the case with bees.
Therefore, Nissan used a rotation function in the robot to avoid collisions in addition to acceleration and slowing.
"This device must process and react to the data every few seconds.
There is no need to store data, nor to use intuitive logic based on previous manoeuvres, so it can operate without interruption with only a few dozen KB memories.
This may sound surprising, but it's not a gigabyte, but we don't even talk about memories the size of megabyte.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision prevention technology, which, according to Nissan's estimates, could enter mass-produced cars within ten years.
The robot is powered by lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more durable than the lithium ion version.
In the future, the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system could be an additional application opportunity to get the driver to the final destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
