Fox in the Henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract with the applicant on the basis of people's drug purchase data.
Data protection professionals fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection programme that always links the use of prescription data to the consent of the person concerned.
This should be in independent hands, otherwise the fox will be left to the henhouse," recalls Richard Dick, the developer of the drug prescription program, Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the amount due in the event of damages dependent on the health of the applicant client, and if they consider the risk to be too high, they do not take insurance with it.
In the past, the person was sent for medical examination, and the contract was concluded only in the light of the results of the investigation.
Dick came up with a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: based on the customer's identification number, he easily obtains the medicines that he has purchased in the last year and a half, and this leads the program to conclude what kind of illness he suffers from and what his health status is.
For example, if you regularly take high doses of cholesterol, it suggests that you have virtually unmanageable high levels of fat in your blood, which immediately lists you as a higher risk category.
Several versions of the programme are on the market, some of them also set a risk factor, so the insurance company has little to do but not just paperwork, although small difficulties arise.
The drawbacks include that some medicines can be used for several uses, for example some compounds can also be used against migraines or hot flushes, but are also effective against depression.
The latter constitutes a significant risk-enhancing factor for business insurers, but not for business insurers.
Separate companies were formed to request and process the data, and they asked the patient's consent before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacies.
They are now bound by the authorities, although they have not been punished for their failure so far.
Some companies have been processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them to drug consumption data so that they can provide a more accurate picture of the patient's health.
More and more companies have access to the data, and monitoring of the use will be increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate health data protection law, but its scope only covers healthcare providers and insurance companies.
Before the convention, there is a bill that gives authorities control over businesses that specialize in reporting.
Dick Richard admits that this is not enough: he therefore improved his programme, which would link the transmission of data to the explicit consent of the data subject.
Another issue is that the data subject cannot deny the consent, otherwise the insurers do not enter into a contract with him.
So the chickens are somewhat dependent on the fox's kindness.
